{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3676714,"name":"David","username":"DavidMasin","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/davidmasin/{size}/205339_2.png","created_at":"2025-07-08T18:51:19.263Z","cooked":"<p>After developing an <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/frc-driver-station-app-for-android/478109">Android DriverStation app</a>, which many in the thread flagged as unsafe for even home use, we pivoted toward something more grounded and practical — especially for Prototypes — that doesn’t require <span class="abbreviation">DS<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Driver Station"></template></span>, Roborio, Radio, etc.</p>
<h2><a name="p-3676714-disclaimer-this-is-not-an-official-way-to-run-motors-1" class="anchor" href="#p-3676714-disclaimer-this-is-not-an-official-way-to-run-motors-1"></a>DISCLAIMER: THIS IS NOT AN OFFICIAL WAY TO RUN MOTORS!</h2>
<h3><a name="p-3676714-it-sends-pwm-signal-to-the-motor-2" class="anchor" href="#p-3676714-it-sends-pwm-signal-to-the-motor-2"></a>(It sends <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> signal to the motor)</h3>
<p>So, for our team’s convenience, we built a reliable and portable solution:<br>
<div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/4X/f/c/0/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7.jpeg" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7" title="20250626_133328"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/f/c/0/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7_2_281x375.jpeg" alt="20250626_133328" data-base62-sha1="zXninFOtosVyR8aaVLHlgtbP5J5" width="281" height="375" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/f/c/0/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7_2_281x375.jpeg, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/f/c/0/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7_2_421x562.jpeg 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/f/c/0/fc02525206ef527eb266af6a1247393750e460f7_2_562x750.jpeg 2x" data-dominant-color="928F8D"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">20250626_133328</span><span class="informations">1920×2560 440 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>
<p>An <strong>Arduino-based controller for two motors</strong> with:</p>
<ul>
<li>Support for synchronized or independent motor control</li>
<li>A 16x2 <strong>LCD screen for real-time <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span> readout</strong> (shown as % output)</li>
<li>Clear, switch-based input for various modes (both motors, same/opposite direction, per-motor toggles)</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3><a name="p-3676714-use-cases-3" class="anchor" href="#p-3676714-use-cases-3"></a><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/bulb.png?v=12" title=":bulb:" class="emoji" alt=":bulb:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20"> Use Cases</h3>
<p>This tool has been super helpful when:</p>
<ul>
<li>PROTOTYPES</li>
<li>Verifying <strong>Falcon 500/Kraken X60 ESC behavior</strong> without radio or roboRIO</li>
<li>Teaching new students about <span class="abbreviation">PWM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Pulse Width Modulation"></template></span>, ESCs, and control systems</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3><a name="p-3676714-hardware-used-4" class="anchor" href="#p-3676714-hardware-used-4"></a><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/hammer_and_wrench.png?v=12" title=":hammer_and_wrench:" class="emoji" alt=":hammer_and_wrench:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20"> Hardware Used</h3>
<ul>
<li>Arduino Uno / Nano</li>
<li>2 Potentiometers (A0, A1 for throttle control)</li>
<li>4 Switches:
<ul>
<li><code>Operation</code> → run both motors</li>
<li><code>Direction</code> → same or opposite direction</li>
<li><code>MOTOR 1</code> and <code>MOTOR 2</code> → enable each motor independently</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>2x Falcon 500 /  Kraken x60</li>
<li>16x2 I2C LCD<br>
<a href="https://cad.onshape.com/documents/7c0da99b9bef22cb5a7513b5/w/f2c3d32eec2da48f595fed30/e/341377c319855829daeb0c9a?renderMode=0&amp;uiState=686d66bfd1b99b7b40a976dd" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">CAD for the box</a>:<br>
<div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/4X/e/0/8/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/e/0/8/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160_2_689x467.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="w2ib602arfMZgZYTxcTl3DeDlBe" width="689" height="467" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/e/0/8/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160_2_689x467.png, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/e/0/8/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160_2_1033x700.png 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/4X/e/0/8/e087edb634029894ba3e602f6a0936bc7545d160.png 2x" data-dominant-color="D3C7B9"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">1292×875 108 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></li>
</ul>
<h2><a name="p-3676714-frc_arduino604x500uploadtq7ccfjq5hqcqesilswf1zcgop0jpeg-5" class="anchor" href="#p-3676714-frc_arduino604x500uploadtq7ccfjq5hqcqesilswf1zcgop0jpeg-5"></a><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/4X/c/e/3/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba.jpeg" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba" title="FRC_Arduino"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/c/e/3/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba_2_604x500.jpeg" alt="FRC_Arduino" data-base62-sha1="tq7ccFJq5HQCQESIlswF1ZCgoP0" width="604" height="500" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/c/e/3/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba_2_604x500.jpeg, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/c/e/3/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba_2_906x750.jpeg 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/4X/c/e/3/ce32ccbb820d65b7e89f504f82b0cfb462711aba_2_1208x1000.jpeg 2x" data-dominant-color="D3D6CF"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">FRC_Arduino</span><span class="informations">1920×1589 131 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></h2>
